      "force `t = 1`, `s = 1`, and `E = A`, which is impossible because `A` is not between `A` and `C` unless `A = C`. \n\nBut perhaps I made a mistake: `wbtw A E C` is equivalent to `∃ t ∈ [0,1], E = (1 - t)A + t C`. \n\nIndeed, `Wbtw` in Lean is defined for three points `A, E, C` as `∃ t, E = (1 - t)A + t C`. \n\nSo, `E = (1 - t)A + t C` and `F = (1 - s)A + s B`. \n\nAssuming `E = F`, then `(1 - t)A + t C = (1 - s)A + s B`, which implies `(t - s)A + s B + (t - 1)C = 0`. \n\nBut `A, B, C` are affinely independent. Then, `t - s = s = t - 1 = 0`. So `s = 0`, which implies `t - s = 0` and thus `t = 0`, but then `t - 1 = -1 ≠ 0`. Contradiction?\n\nActually, no: the condition is that coefficients sum to 0. The above is `(t - s) + s + (t - 1) = 2t - 1`. \n\nAlternatively, we have `(1 - t)A + t C = (1 - s)A + s B`. Then, rewrite as `(1 - t - (1 - s))A + 0B + (t - 0)C - s B = 0`, which is messy. \n\nBetter: `(1 - t)A + t C - (1 - s)A - s B = 0`, so `(s - t)A + t C - s B = 0`. \n\nNow, `A, B, C` are affinely independent, so we can write this as `aA + bB + cC = 0`, with `a = s - t`, `b = -s`, `c = t`, and `a + b + c = (s - t) - s + t = 0`. \n\nThen, `a + b + c = 0`, so by affine independence, if `aA + bB + cC = 0`, then `a = b = c = 0`. \n\nThus, `s - t = 0`, `-s = 0`, `t = 0`. So `s = 0`, `s = t`, hence `t = 0`. \n\nTherefore, if `E = F`, we deduce `s = t = 0`. \n\nBut then, `E = (1 - t)A + t C = A`, and `F = (1 - s)A + s B = A`, so `E = A` and `F = A`. \n\nThen, `wbtw A E C` becomes `∃ t', E = (1 - t')A + t' C`, but since `E = A`, we get `A = (1 - t')A + t' C`, which implies `t'(C - A) = 0`. Since `C ≠ A` (as `AC < AB` and `A, B, C` are not collinear), `t' = 0`. \n\nThis is fine, because `t' = 0` gives `E = A`, and `wbtw A E C` is satisfied (but only if we include endpoints).\n\nBut the issue is that in Lean, `Wbtw ℝ A E C` is `∃ t, E = (1 - t)A + t C`, and it is satisfied",
